The paper deals with derandomization results in graph theory and computational complexity, which suggests that it could belong to several sub-categories. cs.CC (Computational Complexity) is the most likely category as the paper discusses the hardness of approximation results for coloring, which is a classic problem in computational complexity. cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) is also a likely category as the paper deals with graph products and independent sets, which are fundamental concepts in graph theory and algorithms. cs.IT (Information Theory) is another possible category as the paper mentions the use of low-degree long codes, which are related to error-correcting codes and information theory. cs.CG (Computational Geometry) and cs.GT (Computer Science and Game Theory) are less likely categories, but they cannot be completely ruled out as the paper deals with geometric objects (graphs) and game-theoretic concepts (influential coordinates).
